C.Data Preprocessing

Missing Value Handling

Numerical features Median (robust to outliers) Categorical features Mode (most frequent value)

for(col in names(data)[num_cols]){
  data[[col]][is.na(data[[col]])] <- median(data[[col]], na.rm = TRUE)
}

get_mode <- function(x){
  ux <- unique(x)
  ux[which.max(tabulate(match(x, ux)))]
}

for(col in names(data)[cat_cols]){
  data[[col]][is.na(data[[col]])] <- get_mode(data[[col]])
}

Remove Duplicate Rows 

data <- data[!duplicated(data), ]

Outlier Handling (IQR Capping)

Outliers can heavily influence regression coefficients. IQR-based capping reduces extreme values without removing data points.

numerical_vars <- setdiff(names(data)[sapply(data, is.numeric)], target)  

cap_outliers_iqr <- function(x){
  Q1 <- quantile(x, 0.25)
  Q3 <- quantile(x, 0.75)
  IQR <- Q3 - Q1
  
  lower <- Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
  upper <- Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
  
  x[x < lower] <- lower  
  x[x > upper] <- upper  
  
  return(x)
}

for(var in numerical_vars){
  data[[var]] <- cap_outliers_iqr(data[[var]])
}

Encode Categorical Variables 

data <- fastDummies::dummy_cols(
  data,  
  select_columns = cat_predictors,    
  remove_first_dummy = TRUE,           
  remove_selected_columns = TRUE       
)

Feature Engineering

Creating new features to improve model performance.

data$log_Previous_Scores <- log(data$Previous_Scores + 1)  
data$Hours_Attendance <- data$Hours_Studied * data$Attendance  
predictors <- setdiff(names(data), target)

Feature Scaling

Standardization ensures all predictors are on the same scale.

data[, predictors] <- scale(data[, predictors])

D.Modeling

80% training, 20% testing

# Set a seed for reproducibility so that the random sampling is consistent
set.seed(123)  

# Randomly select 80% of the row indices for the training set
index <- sample(seq_len(nrow(data)), size = 0.8 * nrow(data))  

train <- data[index, ]  
test  <- data[-index, ]

Model Summary

Multiple Linear Regression is used because the target variable is continuous.

model <- lm(Exam_Score ~ ., data = train)  

summary(model)

E.Evaluation 

pred   <- predict(model, test)  

actual <- test$Exam_Score  

RMSE <- sqrt(mean((pred - actual)^2))  

MAE  <- mean(abs(pred - actual))  

R2   <- cor(pred, actual)^2  


cat("RMSE:", RMSE, "\n")
## RMSE: 1.839819
cat("MAE :", MAE, "\n")
## MAE : 0.4753267
cat("R  :", R2, "\n")
## R  : 0.7672245
